empty zero length stringnull vs empty zero length string posted on 19.02.2012 by_akismet-f00491cd406d759be5cfe07cf25b26c5 trả_lời not many end users understand the difference between an_empty string of_zero length vs null we have seen that at times the end users put in an_empty string in a_field and_there are no checks in the system to prevent them from being able to get that data into the database an_empty string of_zero length is not the same as null value in sql server string of_zero length is still a_string with no characters null on the other hand can_mean more than just denoting an_absence of_data maybe the data is not applicable or the data is missing or it is just not present yet classic analogy given in this case is that of_a blank cd with nothing on it vs no_cd lot of_debate is there about the usefulness of_null and_the design patterns but that is not what we want to cover here today we will provide some links in the resources section which cover that topic as well what we want to mention in this post today are the differences between null value vs a_zero length_string and_how the behavior is also different between different rdbms we will cover this for a_couple of_different data types besides the string data type we have blogged about the side effects of_using a_zero length string for an_integer data type column before here today we saw similar issue at client site this time with datetime data type column here is an_example using sql server here declare table table col1 datetime insert into table values 1900 000 the empty string gets converted to the default datetime value of 1900 000 as shown above not really what the end user was expecting and_why we get that particular date because datetime is internally stored as two integers hence the bytes per datetime value the first integer stores the number for computing dates before or after the base date of 1900 01-01_and the second integer has the number of_clock ticks post midnight with each tick being th_of a_second what could be some other issues that this can result into besides silently corrupting the data your sql code that would otherwise expect to work like the is null or is not null checks work anymore in case you were doing this for number column the aggregate functions like avg which otherwise would be ignoring the null value will now count the record the sql code which uses functions like isnull coalesce etc will not function as expected since these fields will not have null value the sorts work as expected since_null and_the empty string and_the subsequent default value that actually gets inserted are not the same thing if you have this column as part of_the foreign key you will get an_error at the time of_the insert itself since instead of_a null value the code will try to insert another default value in and_it will violate the fk constraint any concatenation operations or max min functions_can lead to un-desired_results as always there is no substitute for good design_and good code good design can put checks in place both at the application level validations either at the client side or application layer as well as the db level check constraint to prevent such scenarios from happening note that if you enter in an_empty string of_more than zero length in sql server the result would be the same ansi_padding does effect the storage but the comparison rules remain the same you can read more on that in one of_our previous blog posts here and if we were to use a_varchar or char column the behavior is the same with the difference of_course being that it is string of_length in the case of_a char data-type column declare table table col1 char col2 varchar insert into table values select col1 datalength col1 char_str_length col2 datalength col2 varchar_str_length from table where col1 col1 char_str_length col2 varchar_str_length ----_--------------- ----_------------------ also if you are developer who has worked in both sql_server and_oracle then you would know that the behavior in oracle is bit different it treats_null and_an empty string of_zero length the same way and_it treats an_empty string of_more than a_zero length different than null value this is different than the ansi and_sql server behavior in oracle a_zero length variable length string varchar2 data type is treated as a_null a_string of_more than zero length is not treated as a_null a_zero length fixed length string char data type is not treated as null since char data types are blank padded strings sql select as col1 length len_from dual where is null col1 null sql select as col1 length len_from dual where to_char is null this shows that an_empty string is treated as a_null in oracle and_the default data type of_an empty string is varchar2 since if it were char then automatically its length would have been one as stated above it is always better to check for such issues_and in order to follow the same guidelines across rdbms check for empty strings via client side logic or application layer logic or check constraints at the db_level and_ensure that you are going to put in null if that is what your
